atrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from any of the places in Lancashire, Yorkshire, and the West Midlands, so named in Old English as ‘farmstead at a river confluence’, from <i>(ge)m̄ȳthe</i> ‘river confluence’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mitten","meanings":["English (Sussex):","variant of   Mitton  . The English surname in this spelling has been established in Ireland (Wexford) since the early 17th century.","topographic name from Middle English <i>midde</i> + <i>tune</i>, for a dweller in the ‘middle of the village’."]},{"name":"Mittan","meanings":["English: variant of   Mitton  ."]},{"name":"Mutton","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Northamptonshire):","nickname from Middle English <i>motoun</i> ‘sheep’ (Old French <i>mouton</i>).","variant of   Mitton  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Mitton was born in 1328, in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Hankyn Mytton in 1348, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1328–":"1328–Surnud","1316–Male":"1316–Surnud","1349–1424":"1349–142